# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: choke-electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:choke-electronics/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:choke-electronics/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] An **audio frequency** or **audible frequency** (**AF**) is a periodic vibration whose frequency is audible to the average human.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] The SI unit of frequency is the hertz (Hz).
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] It is the property of sound that most determines pitch.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] The generally accepted standard hearing range for humans is 20 to 20,000 Hz (20 kHz).
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] In air at atmospheric pressure, these represent sound waves with wavelengths of 17 metres (56 ft) to 1.7 centimetres (0.67 in).
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] Frequencies below 20 Hz are generally felt rather than heard, assuming the amplitude of the vibration is great enough.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] Sound waves that have frequencies below 20 Hz are called infrasonic and those above 20 kHz are called ultrasonic.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] Sound propagates as mechanical vibration waves of pressure and displacement, in air or other substances.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] In general, frequency components of a sound determine its "color", its timbre.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] When speaking about the frequency (in singular) of a sound, it means the property that most determines its pitch.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] Higher pitches have higher frequency, and lower pitches have lower frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] The frequencies an ear can hear are limited to a specific range of frequencies.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] The audible frequency range for humans is typically given as being between about 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz (20 kHz), though the high frequency limit usually reduces with age.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] Other species have different hearing ranges.
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] For example, some dog breeds can perceive vibrations up to 60,000 Hz (60 kHz).
[src:choke-electronics/audio-frequency] In many media, such as air, the speed of sound is approximately independent of frequency, so the wavelength of the sound waves (distance between repetitions) is approximately inversely proportional to frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] The **basket winding** method is used for coils designed for use at frequencies of 50 kHz and higher to reduce two undesirable side effects, *proximity effect* and *parasitic capacitance*, that arise in long parallel segments of current-carrying wire.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] The proximity effect is caused in a wire by the magnetic field from current flowing in nearby parallel wires, such as other loops in the same coil.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] If two adjacent wires carry a current in the same direction, then the effect is felt in both – the magnetic field of the nearby wires causes current in each wire to be concentrated in a small region on the wire’s surface farthest from the adjacent wires.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] The concentration of current along a small portion of the conductor increases the wire’s resistance and hence increases energy loss.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] At medium and high radio frequencies the increased resistance of the inductor can increase the bandwidth of tuned circuits and reduce the circuit’s frequency selectivity, or Q factor.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] Parasitic capacitance is the consequence of parallel turns of wire acting as capacitor plates, storing charge between adjacent wires.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] The parasitic capacitance can cause the coil to become self-resonant at one or several frequencies, which interferes with the intended tuned resonance and blocks and reflects current at the self-resonant frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] Unfortunately basket-weave coil winding increases the physical size of the coil, which increases leakage inductance.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] Basket windings are often wound with Litz wire, a thin, multi-strand wire with each strand individually insulated, which further reduces losses.
[src:choke-electronics/basket-winding] Cotton or fabric insulation is important from a mechanical point of view during the winding process, because a common enameled magnet wire does not provide sufficient surface friction between coil layers to hold the turns at large angles.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] In electronics, a **choke** is an inductor used to block higher-frequency alternating currents (AC) while passing direct current (DC) and lower-frequency ACs in a circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] A choke usually consists of a coil of insulated wire often wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a doughnut-shaped ferrite bead strung on a wire.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] The choke's impedance increases with frequency.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Its low electrical resistance passes both AC and DC with little power loss, but its reactance limits the amount of AC passed.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] The name comes from blocking—"choking"—high frequencies while passing low frequencies.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] It is a functional name; the name "choke" is used if an inductor is used for blocking or decoupling higher frequencies, but the component is simply called an "inductor" if used in electronic filters or tuned circuits.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Inductors designed for use as chokes are usually distinguished by not having low-loss construction (high Q factor) required in inductors used in tuned circuits and filtering applications.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Audio frequency chokes usually have ferromagnetic cores to increase their inductance.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] They are often constructed similarly to transformers, with laminated iron cores and an air gap.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] The iron core increases the inductance for a given volume of the core.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Chokes were frequently used in the design of rectifier power supplies for vacuum tube equipment such as radio receivers or amplifiers.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] They are commonly found in direct-current motor controllers to produce direct current (DC), where they were used in conjunction with large electrolytic capacitors to remove the voltage ripple (AC) at the output DC.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] A rectifier circuit designed for a choke-output filter may produce too much DC output voltage and subject the rectifier and filter capacitors to excessive in-rush and ripple currents if the inductor is removed.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] However, modern electrolytic capacitors with high ripple current ratings, and voltage regulators that remove more power supply ripple than chokes could, have eliminated heavy, bulky chokes from mains frequency power supplies.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Smaller chokes are used in switching power supplies to remove the higher-frequency switching transients from the output and sometimes from feeding back into the mains input.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Some car audio hobbyists use choke coils with automobile audio systems (specifically in the wiring of a subwoofer, to remove high frequencies from the amplified signal).
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Radio frequency chokes (RFC) often have iron powder or ferrite cores which increases inductance and overall operation.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] They are often wound in complex patterns (basket winding) to reduce self-capacitance and proximity effect losses.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Chokes for even higher frequencies have non-magnetic cores and low inductance.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] A modern form of choke used for eliminating digital RF noise from lines is the ferrite bead, a cylindrical or torus-shaped core of ferrite slipped over a wire.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] These are often seen on computer cables.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] A common-mode (CM) choke is a special application where a choke is used to act upon a common-mode signal.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] These chokes are useful for suppression of electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI) frequently introduced on high current wires such as on power supply lines, which may cause unwanted operation.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Reducing this noise is frequently done by using a common mode choke—two parallel coil windings on a single core.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Common mode chokes allow differential currents to pass while blocking signals that are affecting both wires.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Because the magnetic flux produced by differential-mode currents in the core of a common mode choke tend to cancel each other out, the choke presents little impedance to differential mode currents.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] It achieves this by the placement of windings such that they generate equal but opposite fields that cancel each other out for differential mode signals.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] Normally this also means that the core will not saturate for large differential mode currents, and the maximum current rating is instead determined by the heating effect of the winding resistance.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] On the other hand, common mode currents see a high impedance path due to the combined inductance of the windings that reinforce each other.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] CM chokes are commonly used in industrial, electrical and telecommunications applications to remove or decrease noise and related electromagnetic interference.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] When the CM choke is conducting CM current, most of the magnetic flux generated by the windings is confined within the inductor core because of its high permeability.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] In this case, the leakage flux, which is also the near magnetic field emission of the CM choke is low.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] However, the DM current flowing through the windings will generate high emitted near magnetic field since the windings are negative coupled in this case.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] To reduce the near magnetic field emission, a twisted winding structure can be applied to the CM choke.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] The difference between the balanced twisted windings CM choke and conventional balanced two winding CM choke is that the windings interact in the center of the core open window.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] When it is conducting CM current, the balanced twisted winding CM inductor can provide identical CM inductance as the conventional CM inductor.
[src:choke-electronics/choke-electronics] When it is conducting DM current, the equivalent current loops will generate inversed direction magnetic fields in space so that they tend to cancel each other.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] In electrical engineering, a **common-mode signal** is the identical component of voltage present at both input terminals of an electrical device.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] In telecommunication, the common-mode signal on a transmission line is also known as **longitudinal voltage**.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] In most electrical circuits, desired signals are transferred by a differential voltage between two conductors.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] When referenced to the local common or ground, a common-mode signal appears on both lines of a two-wire cable, in phase and with equal amplitudes.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Technically, a common-mode voltage is one-half the vector sum of the voltages from each conductor of a balanced circuit to local ground or common.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Noise induced into a cable, or transmitted from a cable, usually occurs in the common mode, as the same signal tends to be picked up by both conductors in a two-wire cable.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Likewise, RF noise transmitted from a cable tends to emanate from both conductors.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Elimination of common-mode signals on cables entering or leaving electronic equipment is important to ensure electromagnetic compatibility.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Unless the intention is to transmit or receive radio signals, an electronic designer generally designs electronic circuits to minimise or eliminate common-mode effects.
[src:choke-electronics/common-mode-signal] Common-mode rejection ratio is a measure of how well a circuit eliminates common-mode interference.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] In electronics, **decoupling** is the prevention of undesired electrical energy transfer (coupling) between subsystems.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] A common example is connecting localized decoupling capacitors close to the power leads of integrated circuits to suppress coupling via the power supply connections.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] These act as a small localized energy reservoir that supply the circuit with current during transient, high current demand periods, preventing the voltage on the power supply rail from being pulled down by the momentary current load.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] Another common example of the use of decoupling capacitors is across the emitter bias resistor of transistor common emitter amplifiers to prevent the resistor absorbing a portion of the AC output power of the amplifier.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] Lossy ferrite beads may also be used to isolate or 'island' sections of circuitry.
[src:choke-electronics/decoupling-electronics] These add a high series impedance (in contrast to the low parallel impedance added by decoupling capacitors) to the power supply rails, preventing high-frequency currents being drawn from elsewhere in the system.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The abbreviations *AC* and *DC* are often used to mean simply *alternating* and *direct*, as when they modify *current* or *voltage*.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Direct current may be converted from an alternating current supply by use of a rectifier, which contains electronic elements (usually) or electromechanical elements (historically) that allow current to flow only in one direction.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Direct current may be converted into alternating current via an inverter.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Direct current has many uses, from the charging of batteries to large power supplies for electronic systems, motors, and more.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Very large quantities of electrical energy provided via direct-current are used in smelting of aluminum and other electrochemical processes.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] It is also used for some railways, especially in urban areas.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] High-voltage direct current is used to transmit large amounts of power from remote generation sites or to interconnect alternating current power grids.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Direct current was produced in 1800 by Italian physicist Alessandro Volta's battery, his Voltaic pile.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The nature of how current flowed was not yet understood.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] French physicist André-Marie Ampère conjectured that current travelled in one direction from positive to negative.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] When French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii built the first dynamo electric generator in 1832, he found that as the magnet used passed the loops of wire each half turn, it caused the flow of electricity to reverse, generating an alternating current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] At Ampère's suggestion, Pixii later added a commutator, a type of "switch" where contacts on the shaft work with "brush" contacts to produce direct current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The late 1870s and early 1880s saw electricity starting to be generated at power stations.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] These were initially set up to power arc lighting (a popular type of street lighting) running on very high voltage (usually higher than 3,000 volts) direct current or alternating current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] This was followed by the widespread use of low voltage direct current for indoor electric lighting in business and homes after inventor Thomas Edison launched his incandescent bulb based electric "utility" in 1882.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Because of the significant advantages of alternating current over direct current in using transformers to raise and lower voltages to allow much longer transmission distances, direct current was replaced over the next few decades by alternating current in power delivery.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In the mid-1950s, high-voltage direct current transmission was developed, and is now an option instead of long-distance high voltage alternating current systems.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] For long distance undersea cables (e.g. between countries, such as NorNed), this DC option is the only technically feasible option.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] For applications requiring direct current, such as third rail power systems, alternating current is distributed to a substation, which utilizes a rectifier to convert the power to direct current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The term *DC* is used to refer to power systems that use only one electrical polarity of voltage or current, and to refer to the constant, zero-frequency, or slowly varying local mean value of a voltage or current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] For example, the voltage across a DC voltage source is constant as is the current through a direct current source.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The DC solution of an electric circuit is the solution where all voltages and currents are constant.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Any stationary voltage or current waveform can be decomposed into a sum of a DC component and a zero-mean time-varying AC component; the DC component is defined to be the expected value, or the average value of the voltage or current over all time.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Although DC stands for "direct current", DC often refers to "constant polarity".
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Under this definition, DC voltages can vary in time, as seen in the raw output of a rectifier or the fluctuating voice signal on a telephone line.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Some forms of DC (such as that produced by a voltage regulator) have almost no variations in voltage, but may still have variations in output power and current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] A direct current circuit is an electrical circuit that consists of any combination of constant voltage sources, constant current sources, and resistors.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In this case, the circuit voltages and currents are independent of time.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] A particular circuit voltage or current does not depend on the past value of any circuit voltage or current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] This implies that the system of equations that represent a DC circuit do not involve integrals or derivatives with respect to time.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] If a capacitor or inductor is added to a DC circuit, the resulting circuit is not, strictly speaking, a DC circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] However, most such circuits have a DC solution.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] This solution gives the circuit voltages and currents when the circuit is in DC steady state.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Such a circuit is represented by a system of differential equations.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The solution to these equations usually contain a time varying or transient part as well as constant or steady state part.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] It is this steady state part that is the DC solution.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] There are some circuits that do not have a DC solution.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Two simple examples are a constant current source connected to a capacitor and a constant voltage source connected to an inductor.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In electronics, it is common to refer to a circuit that is powered by a DC voltage source such as a battery or the output of a DC power supply as a DC circuit even though what is meant is that the circuit is DC powered.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In a DC circuit, a power source (e.g. a battery, capacitor, etc.) has a positive and negative terminal, and likewise, the load also has a positive and negative terminal.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] To complete the circuit, positive charges need to flow from the power source to the load.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The charges will then return to the negative terminal of the load, which will then flow back to the negative terminal of the battery, completing the circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] If either the positive or negative terminal is disconnected, the circuit will not be complete and the charges will not flow.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In some DC circuit applications, polarity does not matter, which means you can connect positive and negative backwards and the circuit will still be complete and the load will still function normally.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] However, in most DC applications, polarity does matter, and connecting the circuit backwards will result in the load not working properly.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] DC is commonly found in many extra-low voltage applications and some low-voltage applications, especially where these are powered by batteries or solar power systems (since both can produce only DC).
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Most electronic circuits or devices require a DC power supply.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Domestic DC installations usually have different types of sockets, connectors, switches, and fixtures from those suitable for alternating current.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] This is mostly due to the lower voltages used, resulting in higher currents to produce the same amount of power.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] It is usually important with a DC appliance to observe polarity, unless the device has a diode bridge to correct for this.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] An automotive battery provides power for engine starting, lighting, the ignition system, the climate controls, and the infotainment system among others.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The alternator is an AC device which uses a rectifier to produce DC for battery charging.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Most highway passenger vehicles use nominally 12 V systems.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Many heavy trucks, farm equipment, or earth moving equipment with Diesel engines use 24 volt systems.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In some older vehicles, 6 V was used, such as in the original classic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] At one point a 42 V electrical system was considered for automobiles, but this found little use.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] To save weight and wire, often the metal frame of the vehicle is connected to one pole of the battery and used as the return conductor in a circuit.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Often the negative pole is the chassis "ground" connection, but positive ground may be used in some wheeled or marine vehicles.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] In a battery electric vehicle, there are usually two separate DC systems.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The "low voltage" DC system typically operates at 12V, and serves the same purpose as in an internal combustion engine vehicle.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The "high voltage" system operates at 300-400V (depending on the vehicle), and provides the power for the traction motors.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Increasing the voltage for the traction motors reduces the current flowing through them, increasing efficiency.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Telephone exchange communication equipment uses standard −48 V DC power supply.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] The negative polarity is achieved by grounding the positive terminal of power supply system and the battery bank.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] This is done to prevent electrolysis depositions.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Telephone installations have a battery system to ensure power is maintained for subscriber lines during power interruptions.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Other devices may be powered from the telecommunications DC system using a DC-DC converter to provide any convenient voltage.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Many telephones connect to a twisted pair of wires, and use a bias tee to internally separate the AC component of the voltage between the two wires (the audio signal) from the DC component of the voltage between the two wires (used to power the phone).
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems use DC for the bulk transmission of electrical power, in contrast with the more common alternating current systems.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] For long-distance transmission, HVDC systems may be less expensive and suffer lower electrical losses.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Applications using fuel cells (mixing hydrogen and oxygen together with a catalyst to produce electricity and water as byproducts) also produce only DC.
[src:choke-electronics/direct-current] Light aircraft electrical systems are typically 12 V or 24 V DC similar to automobiles.
